"I’m an iOS user. For me, it’s just how much more smoother, polished and better designed apps are. Like am I the only one that notices how much better certain apps are for iOS than for Android? Like even Youtube. Fucking Youtube, an app from Google. It looks and feels WAY better and faster and polished on iOS. Jesus. Spotify, Facebook, Instagram, Snapchat, EVERYTHING. Whenever I try to use an Android for a few months, I just fall back because I CANT STAND how ugly, slow and buggy Android apps are.

“Yeah but Android isn’t ugly anymore since material design, what about material design??”
Material Design has FAILED. Completeley. Developers don’t use it, they just do their own design rules and styles that don’t even come close to what material design was supposed to be. Even GOOGLE now introduced “MaTeRIaL deSIgN 2” that had NOTHING TO FUCKING DO with “Material” design anymore! It just looks completely different, like they just wanted to emulate iOS a little bit (for example the whitespaces and the clean animations).

Then there’s the thing I can’t stand with for example Samsung phones, where
you have like 2 clock apps, 3 email apps, 2 music apps, 4 note apps, 3 gallery and 2 calendars. And a lot of other non-useful trash you can’t delete. No thanks.

So that’s that. Don’t comment negatively if you’ve never used an iOS device as daily driver. Because believe me: When you actually try one, you’ll immediately feel how much more beautiful designed and smoother it is than your Pixel, Oneplus or Galaxy S.

p.s. I’ve used a Google Pixel (1st), a Galaxy S8 and a Nexus 6 as daily driver. So yes, I know what Android and it’s apps feel like."

"I’ve just read through various comments, mostly Apple-supporting replies to genuine comments about how much Apple is ripping us off.

Now, this isn’t a new concept for us, Apple have done it for years. Although being ripped off could be subjective, particularly if you don’t use many of the product features.

I switched to Apple when the iPhone 4 was released, since then I’ve had fairly regular upgrades. Each year the new product took the price of last years product, with the old one being knocked down in price until phased out. That was until the iPhone X was released. I’m baffled at how the iPhone X gives Apple the leverage to charge so much more? It’s a new year, new tech, and should be about the same price as the previous years flagship. 

I think it was a test. A test to see how much consumers were willing to pay for a new design. Remember, the iPhone 4 was a brand new design over the 3GS, but the price wasn’t inflated by 50% (or so).

512gb in a phone is quite extreme, particularly with the advent of cloud storage. But, £1449 for a phone with this amount of storage is almost the same price as a current line MacBook. That’s just plain crazy. 

What it has done, though, is pave the way for hugely inflated iPad prices due any day now. Again, there’s no reason for a price hike based on my analogy above, it’s a new year, new products, old flagship prices should remain. But they won’t, you mark my words.

Those ‘complaining’ and being told ‘well don’t buy them then’ are missing the point. The people now complaining are the ones who love Apple products, the ones who have spent thousands upon thousands over the years who are now being thanked by these ridiculous prices. £1449 for a phone. Just repeat that back to yourself. 

The iPhone 8 Plus, which incidentally is the one I use and won’t be upgrading again for quite some time, is kind of old for 2018. It’s price should reflect that, with the X and XS/XS Max taking its place at similar prices to the 8.

It took days for Apple to run out of stock of the new phones for 2018 after release. Days. It used to take just hours, if that.

So yeah, I agree with the complaints, and so should you. If you don’t, you’re part of the reason for yearly price increases to come. We all know Apple’s pricing is premium, but not this year, this year they’re taking the p**s out of you."

"Something overlooked in his review was with the wireless improvements.  Both the Xs and the Xs Max both now have gigabit radios which allow 1000 megabit download wireless speeds.  Sure, 5G is not implemented yet but one feature has been. 4X MIMO.  Multiple in Multiple out.  It\u2019s the feature which allows combining 4 different bands to increase the bandwidth of data downloads.  Think 4 times the speed to do app updates, for example.  The iPhone X has 2X MIMO while this years upgrade has 4X.  This is a significant improvement.  The reason for the weird line next to the speaker on the Xs and the Xs Max is because Apple had to increase the number of antennas from 2 to 4 which forced the line at the bottom of the Xs and Xs Max. This changed provided the ability to have 4X MIMO.  With software upgrades the Xs and Xs Max are therefore 5G ready. Important but little understood improvements.  The Xs and Xs Max also have 2X MIMO for WiFi. This means when using Personal Hotspot others who have MIMO in their phones will see a significant improvement in downloading speed.  All in all an excellent upgrade which should be better marketed so people can better take advantage of these features."

"Correction IP68 is the highest rating aside from diving gear. But IP68 goes farther then the standard rating for example IP68 on a Galaxy is rated for 1.5 meters for half hour while Apples rating is 2 meters for a half hour. As far as I know the IP68 rating can go as far as 3.9 meters I don\u2019t know if time is a factor in the ratings or not I just know all IP68s are not created equal. Where IP68 is good for submersion IP65 is good for water jet and not IP68 the phone in that case would have two ratings not just one. So a lower number does not necessarily mean crappy waterproofing. IP67 is up to 1 meter submersion while IP68 is 1 meter or GREATER. Now I would still listen to the manufacturer like Samsung and keep it at 1.5 meters and not 2 meters like Apple is now announcing their phone can handle. Now make a phone with a diving rating"

"WHY APPLE WINS AND REVIEWERS LOSE:

iPhone XS & XS Max AREN'T for people who already use an 'iPhone X'. They are, as is the case with every new iPhone, aimed at people coming from OLDER iPhones (such as 7, 6s or even 5s/5). 

The idea that Apple makes iPhones ONLY for those who bought last year's iPhone is INSANE. You don't buy an iPhone every year (!) unless you are a famous Youtuber or are filthy rich. 

MOST people that buy one use their iPhone for AT LEAST 2-3 years (some for '5' years, even) before upgrading. Unlike Android flagships, iPhones are traditionally extremely future-proof: the '5S', which released all the way back in *2013*, is STILL getting software updates & running smooth as butter in '2018'.

So.. The industry-first '7 nm processor', the '8-core ML neural engine', the crazy-powerful GPU & ALL the other super hardware upgrades that might seem 'overkill' today are actually there, IRONICALLY enough, so 'people WON'T need to buy a new iPhone for the next few years'..  

Reviewers always fail to take all that into account & end up judging the latest iPhone purely in relation to how it stacks up against its immediate predecessor: So they simply quote the '15%' jump in this and '30%' boost in that. They don't see the '300%' jump that someone coming from a 5S or 6 would experience. Shallow A....F.

While long-time customers, aka the MAJORITY of iPhone buyers, understand Apple's long-term approach & ignore these reviews. 

Which is precisely why iPhone sales are NEVER affected by reviews, however negative or even positive they might be. Cuz for the most part, they're 'unrelatable'."

"MKBHD seeing XS and thinking Extra Small really reminds me of how young he actually is. Before his time (not that it's impossible for him to have heard of them, he probably has), there was an Australian rock band called INXS (pronounced In Excess) that was pretty big worldwide in the 80s and into the early 90s. So for anyone who was a fan of them or was influenced by them, the XS name, as much as Apple says "it's pronounced "ten" not "X"," just sounds like "Excess." Which fits right in with the price. That's what I think they were going for, not extra small. (As an INXS fan, maybe I should have an XS, but I'm still happy with my 6s.)

And no shit you're not seeing a big difference between the X and the XS in terms of speed. Those of us who can only afford to buy a phone every few years are gonna see a huge difference. But while I like the form factor well enough, my 6s is still running just as good as it did when I got it in 2016. I can't really afford a new iPhone, so why buy one when the one I have runs great? When I need a new one, I will gladly pay for the model I really want, and I'll take care of it and expect many years of service from it.

In case any Android guys wander in and actually get this far, I've run Android before. Four Android phones, three of which were flagships. I literally cannot afford to use Android. It's priced me out. An Android phone runs great for a few months, acceptably for a few months, and then it's lag city. So you factory reset it, and then it runs good, but not for the same few months, it's less. Then you unlock the bootloader and flash custom firmware, but it has a bug so you have to flash the next one, and then there's a different bug. Each time you flash, it's like 10-15 minutes waiting for that first boot. What if there's an emergency? You're not gonna get that call. Two and a half years into owning my first iPhone, I didn't know smartphones could hold up so well, so long. Didn't think it was possible. The idea that I can have the same phone for 3 years and not hate it, maybe 4, maybe 5... maybe even six years. I'll happily buy a $1000 or $1200 phone that will last me six years. I won't pay $800-$1000 for an Android phone that will last one, and then another year on custom firmware that may or may not work right. I just can't afford that."
